faq:
  - q: "How do I find my Chinese zodiac sign?"
    a: "Enter your birth year into the calculator above. The Chinese zodiac assigns one of twelve animals to each year in a repeating 12-year cycle: Rat, Ox, Tiger, Rabbit, Dragon, Snake, Horse, Goat, Monkey, Rooster, Dog, and Pig. If you were born in January or February, check whether your birthday falls before or after Chinese New Year, as the zodiac year boundary shifts each year."
  - q: "Does my Chinese zodiac sign change based on my birth month?"
    a: "Your zodiac animal is determined by your birth year, not your month. However, if you were born in January or early February, you may belong to the previous year's animal — the Chinese zodiac year starts at Lichun (Start of Spring, around February 3-5) in BaZi tradition, or at Chinese New Year in folk tradition."
  - q: "What are the 12 Chinese zodiac animals in order?"
    a: "The twelve Chinese zodiac animals in order are: Rat (鼠), Ox (牛), Tiger (虎), Rabbit (兔), Dragon (龍), Snake (蛇), Horse (馬), Goat (羊), Monkey (猴), Rooster (雞), Dog (狗), and Pig (豬). This sequence has remained unchanged for over 2,000 years."
  - q: "Is Chinese zodiac the same as Western astrology?"
    a: "No. Chinese zodiac uses a 12-year cycle of animals determined by birth year, combined with the Five Elements (Wood, Fire, Earth, Metal, Water) and the Heavenly Stems system. Western astrology uses a 12-month cycle of constellations (Aries, Taurus, etc.) based on the sun's position at birth. The two systems are entirely independent."
  - q: "What is the Chinese zodiac element for my birth year?"
    a: "Each zodiac year has both an animal sign and one of five elements (Wood, Fire, Earth, Metal, Water), creating a 60-year cycle. The element comes from the Heavenly Stem of your birth year. Use the calculator above to find your specific element — for example, 1988 is an Earth Dragon while 2000 is a Metal Dragon."
